definition:
A form of memory where inputs are stored in a specific order. When a value is requested, the last value inputted is the first value out. (FILO, First in last out)

i.e. if the numbers 1, 2, 3, 4 are pushed (inputted into the stack) in that order, popping (requesting values from the stack) will give 4, 3, 2, 1 in that order.

Call stack: A specialized stack in a computer which tracks which instruction a function was called from so that it can return to the appropriate address when the function finishes.
